Quality plasma is a requirement for fractionators, all of whom must comply with GMP throughout collection and
processing to ensure safety, quality and manufacturing consistency to maintain their marketing authorization (MA).
Failure to comply with specific requirements can lead to inadequate quality and safety and raise questions about the
suitability of therapies with these final products for patients’ use.

These specific requirements include practices and documentation of:

suitable design and layout for safe and efficient function;

hiring and maintaining trained and qualified personnel;

recruiting and maintaining qualified and regular donors;

checks on donor eligibility;

implementation of safety measures for blood and plasma collection;

testing donations for transfusion-transmissible infectious diseases;

use of validated equipment, reagents, medical devices and procedures;

timely collection and standardized freezing conditions;

appropriate plasma storage and transport facilities and conditions;

periodic quality control testing; and

bi-directional traceability between donations and end-products (4, 8)

Fractionators assess many elements when considering entering into a contract. They may vary between contractors
and go beyond those listed here. It is critical that blood systems work closely with the contract fractionator from the
beginning, to identify gaps and ensure that the provided plasma will be acceptable.

6.2 Considerations for plasmapheresis programmes and
source plasma donors

In some countries, the blood system has achieved a sufficient level of availability of blood for transfusion that meets
appropriate quality standards along with proper oversight of blood collection and component separation. Additionally,
they possess knowledge of GMP standards regarding collecting plasma intended for fractionation by recovering it from
whole blood donations. For these countries, the next step to be considered is initiating plasmapheresis programmes.
These programmes are intended to increase the total volume of domestic plasma suitable for fractionation.

A stringent regulatory environment, as outlined in existing frameworks such as the SoHo or FDA regulations, or in the
practices of WHO-listed regulatory bodies, is a prerequisite for policy implementation and oversight to ensure the
safety of plasma donors.

Requirements vary by country (28) but often include:

health screening for potential and current plasma donors according to strict criteria;

strategies to mitigate the risk of adverse events among specific groups of donors, i. e. deferrals for those with low

body weight or low haematocrit;

limits on how frequently or how much plasma can be donated;

measurement of total serum protein and immunoglobulin G;

inspection and certification and/or licensure of facilities collecting plasma;

regular training and professional development for staff of plasma donation centres;

requirements to track and report any adverse health events associated with a plasma donation and to ensure

